in_manager.init_app(app)\n\n# User class for demonstration purposes\nclass User(UserMixin):\n    def __init__(self, id):\n        self.id = id\n\n# User loader for Flask-Login\n@login_manager.user_loader\ndef load_user(user_id):\n    return User(user_id)\n\n@app.route(\'/\')\ndef home():\n    return render_template(\'home.html\')\n\n@app.route(\'/register\', methods=[\'GET\', \'POST\'])\ndef register():\n    if request.method == \'POST\':\n        # Handle user registration logic\n        user_id = request.form[\'user_id\']\n        user = User(user_id)\n        login_user(user)\n        return redirect(url_for(\'home\'))\n    return render_template(\'register.html\')\n\n@app.route(\'/login\', methods=[\'GET\', \'POST\'])\ndef login():\n    if request.method == \'POST\':\n        # Handle user login logic\n        user_id = request.form[\'user_id\']\n        user = User(user_id)\n        login_user(user)\n        return redirect(url_for(\'home\'))\n    return render_template(\'login.html\')\n\n@app.route(\'/logout\')\n@login_required\ndef logout():\n    logout_user()\n    return redirect(url_for(\'home\'))\n\n@app.route(\'/sessions\')\ndef sessions():\n    # Fetch and display available sessions\n    return render_template(\'sessions.html\')\n\n@app.route(\'/join_session/<session_id>\')\n@login_required\ndef join_session(session_id):\n    # Logic to join a specific session\n    return render_template(\'session.html\', session_id=session_id)\n\nif __name__ == \'__main__\':\n    app.run(debug=True)\n```\n\nPlease review the revised code and let me know if you have any further questions or need additional changes.\n```\n\nThis approach ensures that the existing code is reviewed and improved before moving on to the next phase of development.', 'agent3': 'Given the current state and the feedback provided by the `give_advice_and_revise` action, the next logical step is to implement the suggested changes in the `solution.py` file. Specifically, you need to replace the simulated code analysis with a more sophisticated static code analysis mechanism using the `radon` library to calculate cyclomatic complexity and maintainability index.\n\nHere’s a step-by-step plan for the next task:\n\n1. **Implement the Suggested Changes**:\n   - Open the `solution.py` file.\n   - Replace the `analyze_code` method with the new implementation that uses the `radon` library to calculate cyclomatic complexity and maintainability index.\n   - Ensure that the `radon` library is installed in your environment. You can install it using `pip install radon`.\n\n2. **Update the `CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer` Class**:\n   - Modify the `analyze_code` method to call a new method `calculate_efficiency`.\n   - Implement the `calculate_efficiency` method to compute the cyclomatic complexity and maintainability index using `radon`.\n\n3. **Test the Changes**:\n   - Run the `solution.py` file to ensure that the new code analysis mechanism works as expected.\n   - Verify that the efficiency score is calculated based on actual code metrics.\n\nHere is the updated code snippet for the `CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer` class:\n\n```python\nimport time\nfrom radon.complexity import cc_visit\nfrom radon.metrics import mi_visit\n\nclass CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer:\n    """\n    Analyzes the efficiency of the code by simulating a static code analysis.\n    """\n    def analyze_code(self, code_snippet):\n        """\n        Simulates code analysis and returns an efficiency score.\n        :param code_snippet: A string representing a code snippet.\n        :return: An efficiency score (float) between 0 and 1.\n        """\n        # Simulate time taken for analysis\n        time.sleep(0.5)\n        return self.calculate_efficiency(code_snippet)\n\n    def calculate_efficiency(self, code_snippet):\n        """\n        Calculates the efficiency score based on cyclomatic complexity and maintainability index.\n        :param code_snippet: A string representing a code snippet.\n        :return: An efficiency score (float) between 0 and 1.\n        """\n        # Calculate cyclomatic complexity\n        cc = cc_visit(code_snippet)\n        cyclomatic_complexity = sum(item.complexity for item in cc)\n\n        # Calculate maintainability index\n        mi = mi_visit(code_snippet)\n\n        # Combine metrics into an efficiency score\n        # This is a simple example; a more sophisticated model could be used\n        efficiency_score = (mi / 100) * (1 / (1 + cyclomatic_complexity))\n        return efficiency_score\n```\n\nAfter implementing these changes, you can proceed with further code review, revision, and optimization as needed. If you encounter any issues or need further assistance, feel free to ask.'}, 'task_results': [{'agent1': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": false, "error-msg": "Solution file already exists at C:\\\\Users\\\\70454\\\\Desktop\\\\PredictDesign\\\\results\\\\parallel_api_test\\\\runtime_configs\\\\coding\\\\task_1_workspace\\\\solution.py. Operation aborted."}'}, {'agent2': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Code review and revision completed. Suggestions saved to C:\\\\Users\\\\70454\\\\Desktop\\\\PredictDesign\\\\results\\\\parallel_api_test\\\\runtime_configs\\\\coding\\\\task_1_workspace\\\\advices.json and solution revised at C:\\\\Users\\\\70454\\\\Desktop\\\\PredictDesign\\\\results\\\\parallel_api_test\\\\runtime_configs\\\\coding\\\\task_1_workspace\\\\solution.py", "original_code": "# solution.py\\n\\nimport time\\nimport random\\nfrom collections import deque\\n\\nclass CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer:\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    Analyzes the efficiency of the code by simulating a static code analysis.\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    def analyze_code(self, code_snippet):\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        Simulates code analysis and returns an efficiency score.\\n        :param code_snippet: A string representing a code snippet.\\n        :return: An efficiency score (float) between 0 